This paper is likely to belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) sub-category as it presents a new approach to federated learning, which is a popular topic in machine learning research. Additionally, the paper draws on ensemble learning and knowledge aggregation, which are common techniques in machine learning. 

The paper may also belong to the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category as federated learning is a subfield of AI and the paper presents a new approach to this problem. 

The distributed, parallel, and cluster computing (cs.DC) sub-category is also a possibility as federated learning involves communication between multiple devices. 

The systems and control (cs.SY) sub-category may be relevant as the paper discusses methods for coordinating and aggregating knowledge from multiple devices. 

Finally, the computer vision and pattern recognition (cs.CV) sub-category may be relevant as federated learning is often used in image and video analysis applications.
